like because of the age I am like that was like a big part of like how I experienced

00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:06.439
the Internet, right, was like, oh, actually, the Internet is for you to come and post your

00:18:06.439 --> 00:18:11.479
stuff on, you know, like that was for me really empowering at the time, like back at the

00:18:11.479 --> 00:18:16.920
time. And so like Stack Overflow is part of that that wave, right, of like what is

00:18:16.920 --> 00:18:18.239
Internet technology like?

00:18:18.239 --> 00:18:19.400
What is technology like?

00:18:20.040 --> 00:18:24.800
So it was interesting in like understanding like, hey, how can such an organization be

00:18:24.800 --> 00:18:29.400
sustainable? Like what are ways that like you could build a business on this?

00:18:29.400 --> 00:18:32.680
Because the founders of Stack Overflow were interested in building a business.

00:18:32.680 --> 00:18:37.079
They were not interested in like a Wikipedia style model, like they wanted to build like

00:18:37.079 --> 00:18:38.880
a value generating business.

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:41.400
Like, OK, what are some attempts of that like to go?

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:49.640
And and now kind of after the advent of these LLM tools, which, to be clear, slurped up

00:18:49.640 --> 00:18:54.920
all of Stack Overflow in their training data, you know, like what what does it look like

00:18:54.920 --> 00:19:01.640
now? Like are we in a like a lot of sort of the the back and forth, you know, question

00:19:01.640 --> 00:19:09.479
asking, answering has now moved from a place that like it could be viewed as a communal

00:19:09.479 --> 00:19:15.920
resource. It has all been slurped into places that are not accessible to us as a

00:19:15.920 --> 00:19:21.880
community anymore. So it's like the big the big model training organizations came and

00:19:21.880 --> 00:19:28.839
took they took data that I would say morally belongs to all of us.

00:19:28.839 --> 00:19:31.520
Right. Like morally, ethically, that's our data.

00:19:31.520 --> 00:19:33.880
That's our data as like human beings.

00:19:33.880 --> 00:19:36.439
Right. And they took it and they trained a model.

00:19:36.640 --> 00:19:41.560
And now they have like they have not only like made something they can make money with

00:19:41.560 --> 00:19:44.280
off of and, you know, made useful tools.

00:19:44.280 --> 00:19:51.239
Right. But it means that the the data that was used to make that possible is now not

00:19:51.239 --> 00:19:55.800
being generated at the quantity or in the way that it was before.

00:19:56.040 --> 00:20:01.680
So I think it's super interesting to think about where are we today and what are going

00:20:01.680 --> 00:20:09.359
to be the what are going to be the steps that will keep, for example, our ability to

00:20:10.079 --> 00:20:13.719
get answers to our coding questions, you know, like like what will what will that look like

00:20:13.719 --> 00:20:17.160
going forward? I'm not I mean, I'm not a big doom and gloom person, you know, I'm not

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:19.640
saying like the world's ending and anything like that.

00:20:19.640 --> 00:20:24.640
But I think it's some real questions because what got us to here is not what we are

00:20:24.640 --> 00:20:28.520
doing now because the ecosystem has substantively changed.

00:20:28.599 --> 00:20:30.040
The world has changed.

00:20:30.040 --> 00:20:37.680
The world has changed in terms of what like what like where is that data coming from or

