And now I'm like, I don't know, that's just giving all the stuff away for free is kind

00:21:13.439 --> 00:21:15.520
of. I don't know.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.680
Well, there was like there was there was like an inflection point where I think the

00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:25.359
license for content posted on Stack Overflow changed where prior content prior to that

00:21:25.359 --> 00:21:31.599
date, it became this like massive IP contamination issue where developers would copy

00:21:31.599 --> 00:21:36.719
and paste stuff from Stack Overflow into their company's proprietary code bases.

00:21:36.719 --> 00:21:40.760
And then, you know, if you go to sell a software product that that code would turn up

00:21:40.760 --> 00:21:46.760
during like, you know, IP legal due diligence and say, oh, like you used code from Stack

00:21:46.760 --> 00:21:48.719
Overflow and maybe it could just a small snippet.

00:21:48.719 --> 00:21:53.319
But either you have to figure out how to replace that code with your own IP or you have

00:21:53.319 --> 00:21:57.959
to go and find the original author and ask them for permission to use that code.

00:21:57.959 --> 00:22:02.040
I think in the meantime, it's there was a change to make it more lenient.

00:22:02.040 --> 00:22:06.479
But still, like any content that was posted prior to that date has like the old, more

00:22:07.400 --> 00:22:08.800
more restrictive license.

00:22:08.800 --> 00:22:10.839
But it's interesting.

00:22:10.880 --> 00:22:11.880
It's very interesting.

00:22:11.880 --> 00:22:16.599
The licensing around these kinds of issues is very, very interesting.

00:22:16.599 --> 00:22:23.640
And I think it's I think questions around how these licenses gotten us what we thought

00:22:23.640 --> 00:22:27.599
they were going to get us, like how these like because these these all these open source

00:22:27.599 --> 00:22:33.040
licenses, you know, like like came up and like have been hashed out and whatnot in a

00:22:33.239 --> 00:22:40.439
in a time when like like it was a technologically different kind of time than than what we

00:22:40.439 --> 00:22:41.920
have now in terms of the constraints.

00:22:41.920 --> 00:22:46.079
And people talk about like, OK, can we iterate on these?

00:22:46.079 --> 00:22:48.040
Can we think about these differently?

00:22:48.199 --> 00:22:53.280
Like something that, you know, there's still discussion about is like like iterations on

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:58.199
these licenses that make kind of kind of moral or ethical claims.

00:22:58.199 --> 00:23:04.640
Right. Like like I want to exclude certain kinds of uses like you like there are these

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:10.280
licenses that are like mostly open source ish, but they exclude some uses like maybe

00:23:10.280 --> 00:23:12.439
defense or or something like that.

00:23:12.439 --> 00:23:14.719
So there's that sort of category of iterating.

00:23:15.040 --> 00:23:20.040
There is the category of license that's like mostly open source ish.

00:23:20.040 --> 00:23:26.280
But I put some restraints on, say, how you could how can you can platform it?

00:23:26.439 --> 00:23:29.280
So in full disclosure, Positron has a license like that.

00:23:29.719 --> 00:23:34.079
Positron has a license that is not a true OSI approved license.

00:23:34.280 --> 00:23:35.479
It's elastic license.

00:23:35.479 --> 00:23:41.199
And the reason why we did that was because like our experience as a company working on

00:23:41.199 --> 00:23:44.800
open source software has showed us huge benefit.

00:23:44.800 --> 00:23:45.959
We're huge believers.

00:23:45.959 --> 00:23:47.640
We're committed to open source software.

00:23:47.920 --> 00:23:53.439
The pieces of the software that you can make money by platforming them.

00:23:53.760 --> 00:23:59.719
We ended up making the call that like actually we don't want another giant, say, cloud

00:23:59.719 --> 00:24:07.119
company to be able to like to to get directly revenue from just just making available the

00:24:07.119 --> 00:24:08.400
thing the thing that we made.

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:13.680
So I think like I I've been involved in open source for a pretty long time.

00:24:13.680 --> 00:24:15.239
I'm a huge believer in open source.

00:24:15.319 --> 00:24:19.880
I'm not religious, though, about these specific licenses, because I think they're just

00:24:19.880 --> 00:24:20.719
things we wrote.

00:24:20.719 --> 00:24:22.119
And how are they turning out?

00:24:22.119 --> 00:24:23.680
How do we want to iterate on them?

00:24:23.680 --> 00:24:27.359
Like, like, what do we think is best for us as a community?

00:24:27.359 --> 00:24:29.359
I mean, our company, we're iterating with that.

00:24:29.359 --> 00:24:34.319
We're being really explicit, like this kind of software, like a Python package or an R

00:24:34.319 --> 00:24:37.839
package. It's like MIT, this kind of software.

00:24:38.119 --> 00:24:41.839
We're not going to do MIT anymore because we think it is not aligned with our long term

00:24:41.839 --> 00:24:45.640
goals around the like the sustainability of our of our company.

00:24:45.920 --> 00:24:47.239
Super interesting questions.

